{"amendments":[{"body":"Treat failure to persist the pre-backoff snapshot as fatal in `src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:4622-4644` instead of ignoring `write_run_snapshot()`. The new crash-resume path only works if that `Failed`/`interrupted_run` snapshot actually reaches disk; today the write error is silently swallowed, so a kill or crash during backoff can still leave the project stranded in the old `Running` snapshot with no resumable state.","rationale":"This defeats the main safety guarantee added by the backoff logic. Other snapshot writes in the engine already fail hard when durability cannot be guaranteed."},{"body":"Preserve retry-attempt state across a crash during backoff. `src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:4622-4644` now writes resumable mid-retry snapshots, but `derive_resume_state()` rebuilds every failed resume with `attempt: 1` in `src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:5851-5857`. A restart during the backoff window therefore replenishes the retry budget and can exceed the configured max-attempt limit for the stage.","rationale":"The new mid-backoff resume support changes retry semantics: repeated crash/resume cycles can bypass exhaustion entirely, which makes the configured retry caps no longer authoritative."}],"summary":"Reviewed the retry/backoff/timeout changes across the workflow engine and backend adapters, including the updated tests. I found two correctness gaps in the new backoff-resume path; the timeout enforcement and fatal-classification changes otherwise looked consistent."}